{"title_page": "2019 Luzon earthquake", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox earthquake\n| name = 2019 Luzon earthquake\n| image =\n| caption =\n| map2 = {{Location map | Luzon#Philippines | relief=1\n | label = [[Castillejos]], [[Zambales]]\n | lat = 14.924\n | long = 120.497\n | mark = Bullseye1.png\n | marksize = 40\n | position = bottom\n | width = 259\n | float = none\n | caption =\n  }}\n| alt = \n| map = \n| map_alt = \n| map_caption = \n| pushpin_map = <!-- as per Template:Location map -->\n| local-date = {{Start date|2019|04|22}}<ref name=earthquakeluzon001/>\n| local-time = 5:11:09 pm ([[Philippine Standard Time|PST]])<ref name=earthquakeluzon001/>\n| timestamp = 2019-04-22 09:11:11\n| anss-url = us70003a63\n| isc-event = 615412757\n| duration = 27 seconds\n| magnitude = 6.1 {{M|wp|link=y}}<ref name=earthquakeluzon001>{{cite news |title=Earthquake Information - 22 Apr 2019 - 05:11:09 PM |url=https://earthquake.phivolcs.dost.gov.ph/2019_Earthquake_Information/April/2019_0422_0911_B2F.html |publisher=[[Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology|PHIVOLCS]] |access-date=April 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422131602/https://earthquake.phivolcs.dost.gov.ph/2019_Earthquake_Information/April/2019_0422_0911_B2F.html |archive-date=April 22, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| depth = {{convert|20|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=earthquakeluzon001/>\n| location = {{coord|14.99|N|120.35|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}<br />[[San Marcelino, Zambales]] (18km east of [[Castillejos, Zambales]])\n| fault = \n| type = [[Fault (geology)#Strike-slip faults|Strike-slip]]<ref name=phivolcsexplains/>\n| affected = [[Central Luzon]], [[Metro Manila]], [[Calabarzon]]\n| damages = PHP 539 million (US $10.5 million)<ref name=\"NDRRMC_sitrep_13\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ndrrmc.gov.ph/attachments/article/3754/SitRep_No_13_re_Magnitude_6p1_EQ_in_Castillejos_Zambales_as_of_6AM.pdf |title=NDRRMC Update: SitRep No. 13 re Magnitude 6.1 Earthquake in Castillejos, Zambales |last=NDRRMC |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n| intensity = [[Modified Mercalli intensity scale|VII (''Very strong'')]]\n| pga = <!-- NN ''[[Peak ground acceleration|g]]'' -->\n| pgv = <!-- NN cm/s -->\n| tsunami = None\n| landslide = Mt. Tapungso, Zambales<ref>{{cite news |title=Pagguho sa Mt. Tapungso sa Zambales, ininspeksiyon |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/video/news/04/25/19/pagguho-sa-mt-tapungso-sa-zambales-ininspeksiyon |accessdate=April 25, 2019 |work=ABS-CBN News |language=Tagalog}}</ref>\n| foreshocks = \n| aftershocks = 1,049 <small>(16 felt)</small> (as of May 1, 2019)<ref name=\"NDRRMC_sitrep_13\"/>\n| casualties = 18 dead; 3 missing; 256 injured<ref name=\"NDRRMC_sitrep_13\"/>\n| engvar = <!-- follow article: =en-UK will show 'Epicentre' -->\n| citations = \n}}\nOn April 22, 2019, a 6.1 magnitude [[earthquake]]<ref name=PHIVOLCS_Info_3/> struck the island of [[Luzon]] in the [[Philippines]], leaving at least 18 dead, 3 missing and injuring at least 256 others. Despite the fact that the [[epicenter]] was in [[Zambales]], most of the damage to infrastructure occurred in the neighboring province of [[Pampanga]], which suffered damage to 29 buildings and structures.<ref name=\"gmanetwork.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/692450/18-dead-over-280-injured-in-central-luzon-due-to-quake-ndrrmc/story/ |title=18 dead, over 280 injured in Central Luzon due to quake \u2014 NDRRMC |website=GMA News Online |language=en-US |access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref>\n\n== Casualties ==\nAs of April 29, 2019, the National Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council confirmed 18 deaths, 3 people missing and 256 injuries.<ref name=\"NDRRMC_sitrep_13\"/> Of the 18 reported dead, 5 were reported in the collapsed Chuzon Supermarket in the municipality of [[Porac, Pampanga|Porac]], 7 were reported elsewhere in the town, 2 in [[Lubao, Pampanga|Lubao]], 1 in [[Angeles City]], and 1 in [[San Marcelino]], [[Zambales]].<ref name=\"PNANDRRMC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1067931 |title=Death toll in Luzon quake climbs to 16: NDRRMC |publisher=Philippine News Agency |language=en |access-date=April 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423143144/https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1067931 |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Damage and effects ==\nState seismologists said that Zambales had been spared from the earthquake destruction, despite the location of the epicenter being there, although the reports of fatalities and the damage have yet to be received by the local authorities.<ref name=\"quake005\">{{cite news |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/23/19/why-was-pampanga-worse-hit-by-quake-than-zambales-epicenter |title=Why was Pampanga worse hit by quake than Zambales epicenter? |work=ABS-CBN News |accessdate=April 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423063514/https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/23/19/why-was-pampanga-worse-hit-by-quake-than-zambales-epicenter |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The neighboring province of [[Pampanga]] suffered damage to 29 structures/buildings and was the area most affected by the earthquake, due to the province sitting on soft sediment and [[Alluvium|alluvial]] soil.<ref name=phivolcsexplains/> According to governor Lilia Pineda, several structures in the province were damaged by the quake, including a 4-story supermarket in Porac, the [[Bataan]]-Pampanga boundary arch and the main terminal of [[Clark International Airport]], as well as old churches in [[Lubao, Pampanga|Lubao]] and Porac, where the stone bell tower of the 19th-century [[Santa Catalina de Alejandria Church (Porac)|Santa Catalina de Alejandria Church]] collapsed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/22/19/look-quake-damages-church-other-structures-in-pampanga|title=LOOK: Quake damages church, other structures in Pampanga|publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]]|date=22 April 2019|access-date=April 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422114929/https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/22/19/look-quake-damages-church-other-structures-in-pampanga|archive-date=April 22, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Due to the collapse of the 4-story Chuzon Supermarket, the [[Department of Interior and Local Government]] had to suspend all business permits of Chuzon Supermarket and its branches, as well as to conduct an investigation regarding the collapse of the 4-storey commercial establishment, which was built 4 years ago.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pagguho ng supermarket sa Porac, Pampanga iniimbestigahan |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=moJt-lIAEgQ |accessdate=April 23, 2019|publisher=[[ABS-CBN News and Current Affairs|ABS-CBN News]]|via=[[YouTube]]}} (0:01- ) \"Apat na taon pa lamang nakatayo ang gusali ng Chuzon Supermarket sa mismong bayan ng Porac, Pampanga.\" / (1:54- ) \"Pinasususpendi na ng DILG sa mga lokal na pamahalaan ang lahat ng business permits ng mga sangay ng Chuzon Supermarket.\"</ref> There have been at least 421 aftershocks reported but only 8 were felt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1109603/phivolcs-records-421-aftershocks-so-far|title=Phivolcs records 421 aftershocks, so far|last=Ramos|first=Christia Marie|date=April 23, 2019|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=April 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423011251/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1109603/phivolcs-records-421-aftershocks-so-far|archive-date=April 23, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> in Central Luzon 5 dams were damaged and \"needed immediate repairs\", with an estimated cost of 20 million pesos, according to the National Irrigation Administration (NIA).<ref>{{cite news |title=5 Central Luzon dams, facilities damaged by quake |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/04/23/19/5-central-luzon-dams-facilities-damaged-by-quake |accessdate=April 23, 2019 |work=ABS-CBN News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423101801/https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/04/23/19/5-central-luzon-dams-facilities-damaged-by-quake |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nPHIVOLCS stated that the [[volcano]] [[Mount Pinatubo]], located near the earthquake's epicenter, has not shown any \"anomalous activity\".<ref name=\"quake009\"/> Pinatubo is known for its [[Mount Pinatubo#1991 eruption|major eruption in 1991]], which may have been related to a [[1990 Luzon earthquake|major 7.7 magnitude earthquake in 1990]].<ref name=\"quake009\"/> PHIVOLCS added that the earthquake could not trigger an eruption of Pinatubo, explaining that the volcano's magma supply has not sufficiently replenished since 1991 to allow for an eruption.<ref name=\"quake009\">{{cite news |title=No 'anomalous activity' in Mt. Pinatubo after Luzon quake: Phivolcs |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/video/news/04/23/19/no-anomalous-activity-in-mt-pinatubo-after-luzon-quake-phivolcs |accessdate=April 23, 2019 |work=ABS-CBN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423112038/https://news.abs-cbn.com/video/news/04/23/19/no-anomalous-activity-in-mt-pinatubo-after-luzon-quake-phivolcs |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn April 25, the [[Philippine National Police]] (PNP) released the CCTV footage of the collapsed Chuzon Supermarket; the video shows the actual collapse of the second floor of the building in just 10 seconds after the earthquake.<ref>At 0:39 of video, the earthquake hits at CCTV timestamp 05:07:21 before losing the live transmission at 05:07:28. {{cite news |title=Pagguho ng Chuzon supermarket|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ne0dKFdAu1U |accessdate=April 26, 2019 |publisher=[[News5]]|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Chuzon Supermarket CCTV footage during magnitude 6.1 Luzon Quake {{!}} ANC |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gcYQBAzLcsc |accessdate=April 25, 2019 |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News and Current Affairs|ABS-CBN News]]|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Power ===\n{{Location map+|Luzon|float=right|width=250|alt=Strong earthquakes in Luzon|caption=The 2019 Luzon earthquake (M<sub>w</sub> 6.1) and all\n\n=== Schools, colleges and universities ===\nFollowing the earthquake, classes in all levels were suspended. Numerous schools, Universities and colleges that were affected by the earthquake announced class suspension for April 23 and 24.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mayor Estrada declares suspension of classes in Manila |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2019/04/23/mayor-estrada-declares-suspension-of-classes-in-manila/ |last=Edera |first=Erma |newspaper=[[Manila Bulletin]] |accessdate=April 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422215624/https://news.mb.com.ph/2019/04/23/mayor-estrada-declares-suspension-of-classes-in-manila/ |archive-date=April 22, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=#WalangPasok: Class suspensions on Wednesday, April 24 |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1109912/walangpasok-class-suspensions-on-wednesday-april-24 |last=Mercado |first=Neil Arwin |newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |accessdate=April 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423140258/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1109912/walangpasok-class-suspensions-on-wednesday-april-24 |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Classes, work in some Central Luzon areas suspended Tuesday |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1067852 |publisher=[[Philippine News Agency]] |accessdate=April 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423150232/https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1067852 |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=LOOK: UP Diliman cancels classes after earthquake |last=Tecson |first=Zorayda |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1109312/look-up-diliman-cancels-classes-after-earthquake |newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |accessdate=April 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422120009/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1109312/look-up-diliman-cancels-classes-after-earthquake |archive-date=April 22, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The [[Department of Education (Philippines)|Department of Education]] ordered the thorough inspection of school buildings and facilities in the affected areas.<ref>{{cite news |title=LOOK: UP Diliman cancels classes after earthquake |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1109312/look-up-diliman-cancels-classes-after-earthquake |newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |accessdate=April 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422120009/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1109312/look-up-diliman-cancels-classes-after-earthquake |archive-date=April 22, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> A 10-story building of [[Emilio Aguinaldo College]] along [[United Nations Avenue]] in Manila was reported to have tilted and leaned onto the adjacent building, causing its fiberglass terrace to hit the other building. [[Soil liquefaction]] underneath the building was seen as probable causes. One lane of United Nations Avenue was closed to vehicular traffic to ensure the safety of motorists. An assessment team composed of private and local government structural engineers stated that the building's structural integrity remains intact.<ref>{{cite news |title=No imminent danger for leaning Emilio Aguinaldo College building in Manila, engineers assure |last=Peralta |first=Janine |url=http://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2019/4/23/emilio-aguinaldo-college-no-danger.html |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |accessdate=April 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423065302/http://cnnphilippines.com/news/2019/4/23/emilio-aguinaldo-college-no-danger.html |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Engineers: EAC building tilt could be caused by \u2018liquefaction,\u2019 \u2018proximity of establishments\u2019 |last=Adel |first=Rosette |url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2019/04/23/1911933/engineers-eac-building-tilt-could-be-caused-liquefaction-proximity-establishments |newspaper=[[Philippine Star]] |accessdate=April 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423132223/https://www.philstar.com/nation/2019/04/23/1911933/engineers-eac-building-tilt-could-be-caused-liquefaction-proximity-establishments |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Transport ===\nTrain services in Metro Manila were halted followed by an extensive inspection. All lines were closed for the rest of the day. Train services were expected to resume when the inspection results came out with the findings that the railway system sustained no damage.<ref name=\"TrainStop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com//nation/228723-mrt3-lrt-pnr-suspend-operations-after-luzon-earthquake-april-22-2019|title=MRT, LRT, PNR suspend operations after Luzon earthquake|last=Rappler.com|date=April 22, 2019|website=Rappler|language=en|accessdate=April 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422110537/https://www.rappler.com/nation/228723-mrt3-lrt-pnr-suspend-operations-after-luzon-earthquake-april-22-2019|archive-date=April 22, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A crack on the girder was reported at the [[Recto station|Line 2 Recto Station]], but it came from an existing damage and was not earthquake related according to the Department of Transportation (DOTr). It was also superficial in nature.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2019/04/23/1911917/dotr-recto-station-crack-not-earthquake-related |title=DOTr: Recto station \u2018crack\u2019 not earthquake-related |last=Adel |first=Rosette |date=April 23, 2019 |newspaper=[[Philippine Star]] |language=en |accessdate=April 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423100353/https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2019/04/23/1911917/dotr-recto-station-crack-not-earthquake-related |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Rescue efforts ==\nThe authorities began the search and rescue operations for the survivors in the collapsed supermarket in Porac; however, the operation was suspended when a 4.5-magnitude aftershock hit the neighboring town in Castillejos, Zambales on April 24 at 2:02am ([[Philippine Standard Time|PST]]).<ref>{{cite news |title=Magnitude 4.5 aftershock jolts Zambales, felt in Metro Manila |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/24/19/magnitude-45-aftershock-jolts-zambales-felt-in-metro-manila |work=ABS-CBN News |access-date=April 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424145330/https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/24/19/magnitude-45-aftershock-jolts-zambales-felt-in-metro-manila |archive-date=April 24, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=Michael Joe T. Delizo |title=Search for survivors in Porac rubble halted temporarily due to aftershocks |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/24/19/search-suspended-in-porac-supermarket-after-strong-aftershock |accessdate=April 24, 2019 |work=ABS-CBN News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423230540/https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/24/19/search-suspended-in-porac-supermarket-after-strong-aftershock |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[1968 Casiguran earthquake]]\n*[[1990 Luzon earthquake]]\n*[[1999 Luzon earthquake]]\n*[[2019 Visayas earthquake]] - a similar, but unrelated, earthquake that occurred less than a day later\n*[[Manila Trench]]\n*[[Philippine Trench]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ReliefWeb-link|eq-2019-000035-phl}}\n*{{EQ-isc-link|615412757}}\n\n{{Earthquakes in 2019}}\n{{Earthquakes in the Philippines}}\n{{Rodrigo Duterte}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Luzon earthquake, 2019}}\n[[Category:2019 disasters in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:2019 earthquakes]]\n[[Category:Earthquakes in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:April 2019 events in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:History of Luzon|2019 Luzon earthquake]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox earthquake\n| name = 2019 Luzon earthquake\n| image =\n| caption =\n| map2 = {{Location map | Luzon#Philippines | relief=1\n | label = [[Castillejos]], [[Zambales]]\n | lat = 14.924\n | long = 120.497\n | mark = Bullseye1.png\n | marksize = 40\n | position = bottom\n | width = 259\n | float = none\n | caption =\n  }}\n| alt = \n| map = \n| map_alt = \n| map_caption = \n| pushpin_map = <!-- as per Template:Location map -->\n| local-date = {{Start date|2019|04|22}}<ref name=earthquakeluzon001/>\n| local-time = 5:11:09 pm ([[Philippine Standard Time|PST]])<ref name=earthquakeluzon001/>\n| timestamp = 2019-04-22 09:11:11\n| anss-url = us70003a63\n| isc-event = 615412757\n| duration = 27 seconds\n| magnitude = 6.1 {{M|wp|link=y}}<ref name=earthquakeluzon001>{{cite news |title=Earthquake Information - 22 Apr 2019 - 05:11:09 PM |url=https://earthquake.phivolcs.dost.gov.ph/2019_Earthquake_Information/April/2019_0422_0911_B2F.html |publisher=[[Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology|PHIVOLCS]] |access-date=April 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422131602/https://earthquake.phivolcs.dost.gov.ph/2019_Earthquake_Information/April/2019_0422_0911_B2F.html |archive-date=April 22, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| depth = {{convert|20|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=earthquakeluzon001/>\n| location = {{coord|14.99|N|120.35|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}<br />[[San Marcelino, Zambales]] (18km east of [[Castillejos, Zambales]])\n| fault = \n| type = [[Fault (geology)#Strike-slip faults|Strike-slip]]<ref name=phivolcsexplains/>\n| affected = [[Central Luzon]], [[Metro Manila]], [[Calabarzon]]\n| damages = PHP 539 million (US $10.5 million)<ref name=\"NDRRMC_sitrep_13\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ndrrmc.gov.ph/attachments/article/3754/SitRep_No_13_re_Magnitude_6p1_EQ_in_Castillejos_Zambales_as_of_6AM.pdf |title=NDRRMC Update: SitRep No. 13 re Magnitude 6.1 Earthquake in Castillejos, Zambales |last=NDRRMC |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n| intensity = [[Modified Mercalli intensity scale|VII (''Very strong'')]]\n| pga = <!-- NN ''[[Peak ground acceleration|g]]'' -->\n| pgv = <!-- NN cm/s -->\n| tsunami = None\n| landslide = Mt. Tapungso, Zambales<ref>{{cite news |title=Pagguho sa Mt. Tapungso sa Zambales, ininspeksiyon |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/video/news/04/25/19/pagguho-sa-mt-tapungso-sa-zambales-ininspeksiyon |accessdate=April 25, 2019 |work=ABS-CBN News |language=Tagalog}}</ref>\n| foreshocks = \n| aftershocks = 1,049 <small>(16 felt)</small> (as of May 1, 2019)<ref name=\"NDRRMC_sitrep_13\"/>\n| casualties = 18 dead; 3 missing; 256 injured<ref name=\"NDRRMC_sitrep_13\"/>\n| engvar = <!-- follow article: =en-UK will show 'Epicentre' -->\n| citations = \n}}\nOn April 22, 2019, a 6.1 magnitude [[earthquake]]<ref name=PHIVOLCS_Info_3/> struck the island of [[Luzon]] in the [[Philippines]], leaving at least 18 dead, 3 missing and injuring at least 256 others. Despite the fact that the [[epicenter]] was in [[Zambales]], most of the damage to infrastructure occurred in the neighboring province of [[Pampanga]], which suffered damage to 29 buildings and structures.<ref name=\"gmanetwork.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/692450/18-dead-over-280-injured-in-central-luzon-due-to-quake-ndrrmc/story/ |title=18 dead, over 280 injured in Central Luzon due to quake \u2014 NDRRMC |website=GMA News Online |language=en-US |access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref>\n\n== Earthquake ==\n[[File:2019-04-22 Gutad, Philippines M6.1 earthquake shakemap (USGS).jpg|thumb|250px|[[United States Geological Survey]] shake map for the 2019 Luzon earthquake; a maximum [[Mercalli intensity scale]] value of 6.6 was observed in Gutad, [[Floridablanca, Pampanga]]]]\nThe [[Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology]] (PHIVOLCS) initially reported an earthquake of magnitude 5.7 striking at 17:11 [[Philippine Standard Time|PST]] with an epicenter two kilometers [[Bearing (navigation)|N 28'''\u00b0''' E]] of [[Castillejos, Zambales|Castillejos]], [[Zambales]]. The report was later revised to an earthquake of magnitude 6.1 with epicenter 18 kilometers N 58'''\u00b0''' E of Castillejos.<ref name=PHIVOLCS_Info_3>{{cite web |url=https://earthquake.phivolcs.dost.gov.ph/2019_Earthquake_Information/April/2019_0422_0911_B3F.html |title=Earthquake Information NO.: 3 |website=Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423083520/https://earthquake.phivolcs.dost.gov.ph/2019_Earthquake_Information/April/2019_0422_0911_B3F.html |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |access-date=April 23, 2019 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe [[fault (geology)|fault]] from which the earthquake originated is yet to be determined, with geologists focusing on two nearby fault systems, the [[Iba, Zambales|Iba]] Fault and the East Zambales Fault, trying to ascertain the source of the earthquake.<ref name=phivolcsexplains>{{cite news |last1=De Guzman |first1=Robie |title=Phivolcs explains why Pampanga was hit hardest by Luzon quake |url=https://www.untvweb.com/news/phivolcs-explains-why-pampanga-was-hit-hardest-by-luzon-quake/ |accessdate=23 April 2019 |work=UNTV News & Rescue |date=23 April 2019 |language=English, Filipino |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423115503/https://www.untvweb.com/news/phivolcs-explains-why-pampanga-was-hit-hardest-by-luzon-quake/ |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Casualties ==\nAs of April 29, 2019, the National Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council confirmed 18 deaths, 3 people missing and 256 injuries.<ref name=\"NDRRMC_sitrep_13\"/> Of the 18 reported dead, 5 were reported in the collapsed Chuzon Supermarket in the municipality of [[Porac, Pampanga|Porac]], 7 were reported elsewhere in the town, 2 in [[Lubao, Pampanga|Lubao]], 1 in [[Angeles City]], and 1 in [[San Marcelino]], [[Zambales]].<ref name=\"PNANDRRMC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1067931 |title=Death toll in Luzon quake climbs to 16: NDRRMC |publisher=Philippine News Agency |language=en |access-date=April 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423143144/https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1067931 |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Damage and effects ==\nState seismologists said that Zambales had been spared from the earthquake destruction, despite the location of the epicenter being there, although the reports of fatalities and the damage have yet to be received by the local authorities.<ref name=\"quake005\">{{cite news |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/23/19/why-was-pampanga-worse-hit-by-quake-than-zambales-epicenter |title=Why was Pampanga worse hit by quake than Zambales epicenter? |work=ABS-CBN News |accessdate=April 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423063514/https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/23/19/why-was-pampanga-worse-hit-by-quake-than-zambales-epicenter |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The neighboring province of [[Pampanga]] suffered damage to 29 structures/buildings and was the area most affected by the earthquake, due to the province sitting on soft sediment and [[Alluvium|alluvial]] soil.<ref name=phivolcsexplains/> According to governor Lilia Pineda, several structures in the province were damaged by the quake, including a 4-story supermarket in Porac, the [[Bataan]]-Pampanga boundary arch and the main terminal of [[Clark International Airport]], as well as old churches in [[Lubao, Pampanga|Lubao]] and Porac, where the stone bell tower of the 19th-century [[Santa Catalina de Alejandria Church (Porac)|Santa Catalina de Alejandria Church]] collapsed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/22/19/look-quake-damages-church-other-structures-in-pampanga|title=LOOK: Quake damages church, other structures in Pampanga|publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]]|date=22 April 2019|access-date=April 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422114929/https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/22/19/look-quake-damages-church-other-structures-in-pampanga|archive-date=April 22, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Due to the collapse of the 4-story Chuzon Supermarket, the [[Department of Interior and Local Government]] had to suspend all business permits of Chuzon Supermarket and its branches, as well as to conduct an investigation regarding the collapse of the 4-storey commercial establishment, which was built 4 years ago.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pagguho ng supermarket sa Porac, Pampanga iniimbestigahan |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=moJt-lIAEgQ |accessdate=April 23, 2019|publisher=[[ABS-CBN News and Current Affairs|ABS-CBN News]]|via=[[YouTube]]}} (0:01- ) \"Apat na taon pa lamang nakatayo ang gusali ng Chuzon Supermarket sa mismong bayan ng Porac, Pampanga.\" / (1:54- ) \"Pinasususpendi na ng DILG sa mga lokal na pamahalaan ang lahat ng business permits ng mga sangay ng Chuzon Supermarket.\"</ref> There have been at least 421 aftershocks reported but only 8 were felt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1109603/phivolcs-records-421-aftershocks-so-far|title=Phivolcs records 421 aftershocks, so far|last=Ramos|first=Christia Marie|date=April 23, 2019|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=April 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423011251/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1109603/phivolcs-records-421-aftershocks-so-far|archive-date=April 23, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> in Central Luzon 5 dams were damaged and \"needed immediate repairs\", with an estimated cost of 20 million pesos, according to the National Irrigation Administration (NIA).<ref>{{cite news |title=5 Central Luzon dams, facilities damaged by quake |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/04/23/19/5-central-luzon-dams-facilities-damaged-by-quake |accessdate=April 23, 2019 |work=ABS-CBN News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423101801/https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/04/23/19/5-central-luzon-dams-facilities-damaged-by-quake |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nPHIVOLCS stated that the [[volcano]] [[Mount Pinatubo]], located near the earthquake's epicenter, has not shown any \"anomalous activity\".<ref name=\"quake009\"/> Pinatubo is known for its [[Mount Pinatubo#1991 eruption|major eruption in 1991]], which may have been related to a [[1990 Luzon earthquake|major 7.7 magnitude earthquake in 1990]].<ref name=\"quake009\"/> PHIVOLCS added that the earthquake could not trigger an eruption of Pinatubo, explaining that the volcano's magma supply has not sufficiently replenished since 1991 to allow for an eruption.<ref name=\"quake009\">{{cite news |title=No 'anomalous activity' in Mt. Pinatubo after Luzon quake: Phivolcs |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/video/news/04/23/19/no-anomalous-activity-in-mt-pinatubo-after-luzon-quake-phivolcs |accessdate=April 23, 2019 |work=ABS-CBN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423112038/https://news.abs-cbn.com/video/news/04/23/19/no-anomalous-activity-in-mt-pinatubo-after-luzon-quake-phivolcs |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn April 25, the [[Philippine National Police]] (PNP) released the CCTV footage of the collapsed Chuzon Supermarket; the video shows the actual collapse of the second floor of the building in just 10 seconds after the earthquake.<ref>At 0:39 of video, the earthquake hits at CCTV timestamp 05:07:21 before losing the live transmission at 05:07:28. {{cite news |title=Pagguho ng Chuzon supermarket|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ne0dKFdAu1U |accessdate=April 26, 2019 |publisher=[[News5]]|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Chuzon Supermarket CCTV footage during magnitude 6.1 Luzon Quake {{!}} ANC |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gcYQBAzLcsc |accessdate=April 25, 2019 |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News and Current Affairs|ABS-CBN News]]|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Power ===\n{{Location map+|Luzon|float=right|width=250|alt=Strong earthquakes in Luzon|caption=The 2019 Luzon earthquake (M<sub>w</sub> 6.1) and all large earthquakes (M<sub>w</sub> \u2265 7.0) in [[Central Luzon]]. These were in [[1968 Casiguran earthquake|1968 (Casiguran)]], 1970,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/eventpage/iscgem796378|title=M 7.4 - Luzon, Philippines|publisher=United States Geological Survey|accessdate=March 14, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315070542/https://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/eventpage/iscgem796378|archive-date=March 15, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> 1977 (in [[Cagayan Valley]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/eventpage/usp0000myv|title=M 7.0 - Luzon, Philippines|publisher=United States Geological Survey|accessdate=March 14, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315070544/https://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/eventpage/usp0000myv|archive-date=March 15, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> 1985,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/eventpage/usp0002e2z|title=M 7.0 - Luzon, Philippines|publisher=United States Geological Survey|accessdate=March 14, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315070635/https://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/eventpage/usp0002e2z|archive-date=March 15, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[1990 Luzon earthquake|1990]], and [[1999 Luzon earthquake|1999]].<br> Geologically, to the left is the [[Manila Trench]] and the Iba Fault in [[Zambales]]. In the center is the Digdig Fault in [[Nueva Ecija]]. To the right is the diagonal Casiguran Fault in [[Aurora (province)|Aurora]], then the [[East Luzon Trench]].|places=\n{{Location map~|Luzon|lat=15.4|long=120.7|position=right|label=<div style=\"position: relative; top: 0.4em;\">1985</div>}}\n{{Location map~|Luzon|lat=15.68|long=121.2|position=right|label=<div style=\"position: relative; top: 0.4em;\">[[1990 Luzon earthquake|'''1990''']]</div>}}\n{{Location map~|Luzon|lat=15.83|long=121.6|position=right|label=<div style=\"position: relative; top: 0.4em;\">1970</div>}}\n{{Location map~|Luzon|lat=16.32|long=122.0|position=right|label=<div style=\"position: relative; top: 0.4em;\">[[1968 Casiguran earthquake|'''1968''']]</div>}}\n{{Location map~|Luzon|lat=16.77|long=122.3|position=right|label=<div style=\"position: relative; top: 0.4em;\">1977</div>}}\n{{Location map~|Luzon|lat=15.7|long=119.7|position=left|label=<div style=\"position: relative; top: 0.4em;\">[[1999 Luzon earthquake|'''1999''']]</div>}}\n{{Location map~|Luzon|lat=15.0|long=120.5|position=left|label=<div style=\"position: relative; top: 0.4em;\">'''2019'''</div>}}\n}}\nPower outages were reported in the provinces of [[Bataan]], [[La Union]], [[Pampanga]] and [[Pangasinan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Power outage hits Bataan, Pampanga after magnitude 6.1-quake|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1109314/power-outage-hits-bataan-pampanga-after-magnitude-6-1-quake|website=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|accessdate=April 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422122721/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1109314/power-outage-hits-bataan-pampanga-after-magnitude-6-1-quake|archive-date=April 22, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> They were also experienced in parts of [[Quezon]], [[Batangas]], [[Camarines Sur]] and [[Sorsogon]], where power supply has since been restored. The [[National Grid Corporation of the Philippines]] (NGCP) issued an alert level at yellow status on the Luzon grid after the initial earthquake.<ref>{{cite news |title=Alert level sa Luzon grid itinaas bunsod ng lindol |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/23/19/alert-level-sa-luzon-grid-itinaas-bunsod-ng-lindol |work=ABS-CBN News |language=Tagalog |access-date=April 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423070252/https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/23/19/alert-level-sa-luzon-grid-itinaas-bunsod-ng-lindol |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Schools, colleges and universities ===\nFollowing the earthquake, classes in all levels were suspended. Numerous schools, Universities and colleges that were affected by the earthquake announced class suspension for April 23 and 24.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mayor Estrada declares suspension of classes in Manila |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2019/04/23/mayor-estrada-declares-suspension-of-classes-in-manila/ |last=Edera |first=Erma |newspaper=[[Manila Bulletin]] |accessdate=April 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422215624/https://news.mb.com.ph/2019/04/23/mayor-estrada-declares-suspension-of-classes-in-manila/ |archive-date=April 22, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=#WalangPasok: Class suspensions on Wednesday, April 24 |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1109912/walangpasok-class-suspensions-on-wednesday-april-24 |last=Mercado |first=Neil Arwin |newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |accessdate=April 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423140258/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1109912/walangpasok-class-suspensions-on-wednesday-april-24 |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Classes, work in some Central Luzon areas suspended Tuesday |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1067852 |publisher=[[Philippine News Agency]] |accessdate=April 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423150232/https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1067852 |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=LOOK: UP Diliman cancels classes after earthquake |last=Tecson |first=Zorayda |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1109312/look-up-diliman-cancels-classes-after-earthquake |newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |accessdate=April 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422120009/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1109312/look-up-diliman-cancels-classes-after-earthquake |archive-date=April 22, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The [[Department of Education (Philippines)|Department of Education]] ordered the thorough inspection of school buildings and facilities in the affected areas.<ref>{{cite news |title=LOOK: UP Diliman cancels classes after earthquake |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1109312/look-up-diliman-cancels-classes-after-earthquake |newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |accessdate=April 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422120009/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1109312/look-up-diliman-cancels-classes-after-earthquake |archive-date=April 22, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> A 10-story building of [[Emilio Aguinaldo College]] along [[United Nations Avenue]] in Manila was reported to have tilted and leaned onto the adjacent building, causing its fiberglass terrace to hit the other building. [[Soil liquefaction]] underneath the building was seen as probable causes. One lane of United Nations Avenue was closed to vehicular traffic to ensure the safety of motorists. An assessment team composed of private and local government structural engineers stated that the building's structural integrity remains intact.<ref>{{cite news |title=No imminent danger for leaning Emilio Aguinaldo College building in Manila, engineers assure |last=Peralta |first=Janine |url=http://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2019/4/23/emilio-aguinaldo-college-no-danger.html |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |accessdate=April 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423065302/http://cnnphilippines.com/news/2019/4/23/emilio-aguinaldo-college-no-danger.html |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Engineers: EAC building tilt could be caused by \u2018liquefaction,\u2019 \u2018proximity of establishments\u2019 |last=Adel |first=Rosette |url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2019/04/23/1911933/engineers-eac-building-tilt-could-be-caused-liquefaction-proximity-establishments |newspaper=[[Philippine Star]] |accessdate=April 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423132223/https://www.philstar.com/nation/2019/04/23/1911933/engineers-eac-building-tilt-could-be-caused-liquefaction-proximity-establishments |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Transport ===\nTrain services in Metro Manila were halted followed by an extensive inspection. All lines were closed for the rest of the day. Train services were expected to resume when the inspection results came out with the findings that the railway system sustained no damage.<ref name=\"TrainStop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com//nation/228723-mrt3-lrt-pnr-suspend-operations-after-luzon-earthquake-april-22-2019|title=MRT, LRT, PNR suspend operations after Luzon earthquake|last=Rappler.com|date=April 22, 2019|website=Rappler|language=en|accessdate=April 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422110537/https://www.rappler.com/nation/228723-mrt3-lrt-pnr-suspend-operations-after-luzon-earthquake-april-22-2019|archive-date=April 22, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A crack on the girder was reported at the [[Recto station|Line 2 Recto Station]], but it came from an existing damage and was not earthquake related according to the Department of Transportation (DOTr). It was also superficial in nature.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2019/04/23/1911917/dotr-recto-station-crack-not-earthquake-related |title=DOTr: Recto station \u2018crack\u2019 not earthquake-related |last=Adel |first=Rosette |date=April 23, 2019 |newspaper=[[Philippine Star]] |language=en |accessdate=April 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423100353/https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2019/04/23/1911917/dotr-recto-station-crack-not-earthquake-related |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Rescue efforts ==\nThe authorities began the search and rescue operations for the survivors in the collapsed supermarket in Porac; however, the operation was suspended when a 4.5-magnitude aftershock hit the neighboring town in Castillejos, Zambales on April 24 at 2:02am ([[Philippine Standard Time|PST]]).<ref>{{cite news |title=Magnitude 4.5 aftershock jolts Zambales, felt in Metro Manila |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/24/19/magnitude-45-aftershock-jolts-zambales-felt-in-metro-manila |work=ABS-CBN News |access-date=April 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424145330/https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/24/19/magnitude-45-aftershock-jolts-zambales-felt-in-metro-manila |archive-date=April 24, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=Michael Joe T. Delizo |title=Search for survivors in Porac rubble halted temporarily due to aftershocks |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/24/19/search-suspended-in-porac-supermarket-after-strong-aftershock |accessdate=April 24, 2019 |work=ABS-CBN News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423230540/https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/24/19/search-suspended-in-porac-supermarket-after-strong-aftershock |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[1968 Casiguran earthquake]]\n*[[1990 Luzon earthquake]]\n*[[1999 Luzon earthquake]]\n*[[2019 Visayas earthquake]] - a similar, but unrelated, earthquake that occurred less than a day later\n*[[Manila Trench]]\n*[[Philippine Trench]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ReliefWeb-link|eq-2019-000035-phl}}\n*{{EQ-isc-link|615412757}}\n\n{{Earthquakes in 2019}}\n{{Earthquakes in the Philippines}}\n{{Rodrigo Duterte}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Luzon earthquake, 2019}}\n[[Category:2019 disasters in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:2019 earthquakes]]\n[[Category:Earthquakes in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:April 2019 events in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:History of Luzon|2019 Luzon earthquake]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7d:46ad:300:b5d9:bf7d:f4ff:66bb", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarthquake:cxcvfdghtersshrhr)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_Luzon_earthquake"}
{"title_page": "World 1-1", "text_new": "{{Infobox fictional location\n| name       = World 1-1\n| colour     =\n| image      = \u96e8\u306e\u65e5\u306f\u30d5\u30a1\u30df\u30b3\u30f3\u3067\u904a\u3079\u308b (15441664223).jpg\n| imagesize  = \n| caption    = ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'' (original [[Nintendo Entertainment System|Family Computer]] version) on World 1-1.\n| source     =\n| creator    = [[Shigeru Miyamoto]]\n| genre      = [[Platform game|Platforming]]\n| people     = [[Mario]], [[Koopa Troopa]], [[Goomba]]\n| first      = ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'' (1985)\n}}\n'''World 1-1''' is the first [[level (video gaming)|level]] of ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'', [[Nintendo]]'s 1985 [[platform game]] for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]]. The level was designed by [[Shigeru Miyamoto]] to be a [[Tutorial (video gaming)|tutorial]] for new players, orienting them to platform jumping and to the rest of the game. World 1-1 is one of the most iconic video game levels and has been widely imitated and parodied.\n\n==Design==\n===Design philosophy===\nDuring the [[third generation of video game consoles]], tutorials which explain the mechanics of a video game were rare, and players instead were oriented to a new video game by its [[level design]]. The opening sections of [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] games such as ''[[Metroid (video game)|Metroid]]'', ''[[The Legend of Zelda (video game)|The Legend of Zelda]]'', and ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'' are all designed in such a way that players are forced to explore the mechanics of the game to be able to advance. ''Super Mario Bros.'' is the first [[side-scrolling]] video game featuring [[Mario]], and one of the first [[Shigeru Miyamoto gameography|video games directed and designed by Shigeru Miyamoto]]. Rather than confront the player with obstacles indiscriminately, the first level of ''Super Mario Bros.'' introduces the variety of hazards and objects by forcing the player to interact with them while advancing through the level.<ref name=1UP>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/features/learning-level-design-mario|website=[[1UP.com]]|title=Learning Through Level Design with Mario|last=Parish|first=Jeremy|year=2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120818210917/http://www.1up.com/features/learning-level-design-mario|archivedate=August 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with ''[[Eurogamer]]'', Miyamoto explained that he designed World 1-1 to contain everything a player needs to \"gradually and naturally understand what they\u2019re doing\", so that they can quickly understand how the game works. According to Miyamoto, once the player understands the mechanics of the game, the player will be able to play more freely and it becomes \"their game\".<ref name=Eurogamer>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-09-07-video-miyamoto-on-how-nintendo-made-marios-most-iconic-level|website=[[Eurogamer]]|title=Video: Miyamoto on how Nintendo made Mario's most iconic level|last=Robinson|first=Martin|date=September 7, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Gamasutra>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/253150/How_Miyamoto_built_Super_Mario_Bros_legendary_World_11.php|website=[[Gamasutra]]|title=How Miyamoto built ''Super Mario Bros.''{{'}} legendary World 1-1|last=Kerr|first=Chris|date=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nYo yo yo... I'm be editing sis secton\n\n==Reception==\nWorld 1-1 has been cited as one of the most iconic video game levels, with Chris Kerr of ''Gamasutra'' describing it as \"legendary\".<ref name=Eurogamer /><ref name=Gamasutra /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2015/09/07/watch-miyamoto-explain-how-he-designed-super-mario-bros-world-1-1/|website=[[VG247]]|title=Watch Miyamoto explain how he designed Super Mario Bros. World 1-1|last=Saed|first=Sherif|date=September 7, 2015}}</ref> Boston Blake of ''Game Rant'' rated World 1-1 among the best opening levels in video games as a level that \"ignited a love for gaming in the hearts of gamers around the world\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamerant.com/best-video-game-opening-levels/|publisher=Game Rant|title=The Top 10 Opening Levels in Video Games|last=Blake|first=Boston|date= September 2015}}</ref> and Jon Irwin of ''[[Paste Magazine]]'' described the level as a \"master-class in teaching players how to play\".<ref name=Paste>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/09/the-20-best-2d-mario-levels-of-all-time.html|magazine=[[Paste Magazine]]|title=The 20 Best 2D Mario Levels of All Time|last=Irwin|first=Jon|date=September 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nJeremy Parish of ''[[1UP.com]]'' stated that \"much of the game's success arose from the fact that it equipped players with the tools to master it from the very beginning.\" Almost all mechanics introduced later in the game are variations of what the player learns in World 1-1, and the first levels of later games in the series (such as ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'') also expand upon the mechanics introduced in World 1-1. Parish described the stage as \"the most widely imitated, referenced, and parodied single level of a video game\".<ref name=1UP />\n\n===Legacy===\nThe design philosophy introduced in ''Super Mario Bros.'', described as \"learning through play\", has been implemented in all video games Miyamoto has worked on since.<ref name=Eurogamer /> World 1-1 greatly influenced later ''[[Super Mario]]'' games, such as ''[[Super Mario 3D World]]''{{'}}s first level.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/how-spirit-original-world-1-1-carries-todays-mario-225218|newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]]|title=How the spirit of the original World 1-1 carries on in today\u2019s Mario games|last=Gerardi|first=Matt|date=July 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nVariations of World 1-1 are frequently recreated by fans in the ''[[Super Mario Maker]]'' series. Examples include an extra difficult version where dozens of twirling fire bars are added to the level, a version in which the level needs to be climbed vertically, and version of World 1-1 that plays itself automatically.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/7/16/20696152/super-mario-maker-2-world-1-1-nintendo-switch|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|title=Mario Maker 2 level turns World 1-1 into a fiery nightmare hellscape|last=Diaz|first=Ana|date=2019-07-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/nintendo-switch/2019/8/21/20826916/super-mario-maker-2-weird-levels-1-1-on-side-nintendo-switch|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|title=Super Mario Maker 2 level turns World 1-1 on its side|last=Good|first=Owen S.|date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/super-mario-maker-2-best-levels/automatic-1-1|work=[[Complex.com|Complex]]|title=The Best 'Super Mario Maker 2' Levels for Nintendo Switch|author=Khal|date=2019-08-13}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Super Mario Bros. theme|''Super Mario Bros.'' theme]]\n*[[Green Hill Zone]]\n*[[Level design]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Mario series}}\n\n[[Category:1985 in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional elements introduced in 1985]]\n[[Category:Mario]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Entertainment System]]\n[[Category:Video game levels]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox fictional location\n| name       = World 1-1\n| colour     =\n| image      = \u96e8\u306e\u65e5\u306f\u30d5\u30a1\u30df\u30b3\u30f3\u3067\u904a\u3079\u308b (15441664223).jpg\n| imagesize  = \n| caption    = ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'' (original [[Nintendo Entertainment System|Family Computer]] version) on World 1-1.\n| source     =\n| creator    = [[Shigeru Miyamoto]]\n| genre      = [[Platform game|Platforming]]\n| people     = [[Mario]], [[Koopa Troopa]], [[Goomba]]\n| first      = ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'' (1985)\n}}\n'''World 1-1''' is the first [[level (video gaming)|level]] of ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'', [[Nintendo]]'s 1985 [[platform game]] for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]]. The level was designed by [[Shigeru Miyamoto]] to be a [[Tutorial (video gaming)|tutorial]] for new players, orienting them to platform jumping and to the rest of the game. World 1-1 is one of the most iconic video game levels and has been widely imitated and parodied.\n\n==Design==\n===Design philosophy===\nDuring the [[third generation of video game consoles]], tutorials which explain the mechanics of a video game were rare, and players instead were oriented to a new video game by its [[level design]]. The opening sections of [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] games such as ''[[Metroid (video game)|Metroid]]'', ''[[The Legend of Zelda (video game)|The Legend of Zelda]]'', and ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'' are all designed in such a way that players are forced to explore the mechanics of the game to be able to advance. ''Super Mario Bros.'' is the first [[side-scrolling]] video game featuring [[Mario]], and one of the first [[Shigeru Miyamoto gameography|video games directed and designed by Shigeru Miyamoto]]. Rather than confront the player with obstacles indiscriminately, the first level of ''Super Mario Bros.'' introduces the variety of hazards and objects by forcing the player to interact with them while advancing through the level.<ref name=1UP>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/features/learning-level-design-mario|website=[[1UP.com]]|title=Learning Through Level Design with Mario|last=Parish|first=Jeremy|year=2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120818210917/http://www.1up.com/features/learning-level-design-mario|archivedate=August 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with ''[[Eurogamer]]'', Miyamoto explained that he designed World 1-1 to contain everything a player needs to \"gradually and naturally understand what they\u2019re doing\", so that they can quickly understand how the game works. According to Miyamoto, once the player understands the mechanics of the game, the player will be able to play more freely and it becomes \"their game\".<ref name=Eurogamer>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-09-07-video-miyamoto-on-how-nintendo-made-marios-most-iconic-level|website=[[Eurogamer]]|title=Video: Miyamoto on how Nintendo made Mario's most iconic level|last=Robinson|first=Martin|date=September 7, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Gamasutra>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/253150/How_Miyamoto_built_Super_Mario_Bros_legendary_World_11.php|website=[[Gamasutra]]|title=How Miyamoto built ''Super Mario Bros.''{{'}} legendary World 1-1|last=Kerr|first=Chris|date=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Execution===\n[[File:World 1-1 obstacle schematic.PNG|thumb|right|Schematic of the start of World 1-1. The [[Goomba]] (red) walks toward Mario and must be jumped over. The [[Super Mario#Mushroom|Mushroom]] (light green) appears after bumping into the golden block from below, and initially rolls to the right, until it falls off the platform and bounces against the pipe (green). The Mushroom then turns around and rolls toward Mario, who can easily receive it at this point.<ref name=Eurogamer />]]\n\nAt the start of World 1-1, the player\u2014[[player character|taking control]] of Mario\u2014comes across a [[Goomba]] slowly approaching. According to ''[[1UP.com]]'', it is likely that this first enemy will [[life (gaming)|kill]] a new player, even though the enemy can easily be avoided by jumping over it. As very little progress is lost, the player learns from defeat and can try again.<ref name=1UP /> Past this Goomba comes an arrangement of blocks, a few of which are colored in gold. By bumping one of the gold-colored blocks from below, a coin pops out. According to Miyamoto, seeing a coin come out will \"make [the player] happy\" and want to repeat the action. Doing so for the second gold-colored block makes a [[Super Mario#Mushroom|Mushroom]] come out; a [[power-up]], unbeknownst to the player. The player has learnt from the Goomba that just defeated them that mushroom-shaped beings are bad, so naturally the player tries to jump over the mushroom in order to avoid it, however the blocks are arranged in such a manner that a player attempting to dodge the mushroom immediately hits and is deflected by the block downwards onto the mushroom, which lands the player onto the power-up. Being touched by the Mushroom makes Mario grow in size, another positive reinforcement.<ref name=Eurogamer /><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.popularmechanics.com/culture/gaming/a17251/super-marios-bros-world-1-1-explained/|magazine=[[Popular Mechanics]]|title=Why the Famous First Level of Super Mario Bros. Looks the Way It Does|last=Bishop|first=Rollin|date=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter this block formation comes a series of four vertical [[warp pipe]] obstacles that must be jumped over. Each has a different height, subtly teaching the player that the longer they hold the jump button, the higher their jump goes.<ref name=1UP /> When encountering variously-sized pits, the player may discover how to use the button for running, because running makes a bigger jump across the pits. Furthermore, Miyamoto ensured that some pits have floors and can be simply jumped out of instead of forcing the player to retry the entire level.<ref name=Eurogamer />\n\nWorld 1-1 includes a few secrets\u2014such as a warp pipe that leads to a [[bonus level|bonus room]] and a hidden block that contains a [[1-up]]\u2014that players can discover by [[replay value|replaying]]. The warp pipe also allows a player to skip a large portion of the stage, so that more experienced players can advance more quickly in repeat replays of the game.<ref name=1UP />\n\n==Reception==\nWorld 1-1 has been cited as one of the most iconic video game levels, with Chris Kerr of ''Gamasutra'' describing it as \"legendary\".<ref name=Eurogamer /><ref name=Gamasutra /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2015/09/07/watch-miyamoto-explain-how-he-designed-super-mario-bros-world-1-1/|website=[[VG247]]|title=Watch Miyamoto explain how he designed Super Mario Bros. World 1-1|last=Saed|first=Sherif|date=September 7, 2015}}</ref> Boston Blake of ''Game Rant'' rated World 1-1 among the best opening levels in video games as a level that \"ignited a love for gaming in the hearts of gamers around the world\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamerant.com/best-video-game-opening-levels/|publisher=Game Rant|title=The Top 10 Opening Levels in Video Games|last=Blake|first=Boston|date= September 2015}}</ref> and Jon Irwin of ''[[Paste Magazine]]'' described the level as a \"master-class in teaching players how to play\".<ref name=Paste>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/09/the-20-best-2d-mario-levels-of-all-time.html|magazine=[[Paste Magazine]]|title=The 20 Best 2D Mario Levels of All Time|last=Irwin|first=Jon|date=September 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nJeremy Parish of ''[[1UP.com]]'' stated that \"much of the game's success arose from the fact that it equipped players with the tools to master it from the very beginning.\" Almost all mechanics introduced later in the game are variations of what the player learns in World 1-1, and the first levels of later games in the series (such as ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'') also expand upon the mechanics introduced in World 1-1. Parish described the stage as \"the most widely imitated, referenced, and parodied single level of a video game\".<ref name=1UP />\n\n===Legacy===\nThe design philosophy introduced in ''Super Mario Bros.'', described as \"learning through play\", has been implemented in all video games Miyamoto has worked on since.<ref name=Eurogamer /> World 1-1 greatly influenced later ''[[Super Mario]]'' games, such as ''[[Super Mario 3D World]]''{{'}}s first level.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/how-spirit-original-world-1-1-carries-todays-mario-225218|newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]]|title=How the spirit of the original World 1-1 carries on in today\u2019s Mario games|last=Gerardi|first=Matt|date=July 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nVariations of World 1-1 are frequently recreated by fans in the ''[[Super Mario Maker]]'' series. Examples include an extra difficult version where dozens of twirling fire bars are added to the level, a version in which the level needs to be climbed vertically, and version of World 1-1 that plays itself automatically.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/7/16/20696152/super-mario-maker-2-world-1-1-nintendo-switch|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|title=Mario Maker 2 level turns World 1-1 into a fiery nightmare hellscape|last=Diaz|first=Ana|date=2019-07-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/nintendo-switch/2019/8/21/20826916/super-mario-maker-2-weird-levels-1-1-on-side-nintendo-switch|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|title=Super Mario Maker 2 level turns World 1-1 on its side|last=Good|first=Owen S.|date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/super-mario-maker-2-best-levels/automatic-1-1|work=[[Complex.com|Complex]]|title=The Best 'Super Mario Maker 2' Levels for Nintendo Switch|author=Khal|date=2019-08-13}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Super Mario Bros. theme|''Super Mario Bros.'' theme]]\n*[[Green Hill Zone]]\n*[[Level design]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Mario series}}\n\n[[Category:1985 in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional elements introduced in 1985]]\n[[Category:Mario]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Entertainment System]]\n[[Category:Video game levels]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:9003:de00:b8f2:62b6:990b:2f44", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(Yeet)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_1-1"}
