{"title_page": "George Gadson", "text_new": "{{Prod blp/dated\n  |concern = \n  |user = \n  |timestamp = 20200416055337\n  |help = off\n}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = GeorgeGadson\n| image            = Geroge the Classic.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = GeorgeGadson in 2019\n| birth_name       = <!--only use if different from name-->\n| birth_date       = August 10, 1953, Fort Meade, Florida\n| birth_place      = Fort Meade, Florida\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = American\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = Duke University, North Carolina\n| known_for        = Sculpting, Public Art, Photography, Community Artwork\n| notable_works    = Sculpture: \u201cThe Quarterback\u201d and the \u201cThe Kicker\u201d\n| style            = \n| movement         = \n| awards           = Art and Visionary Award 2019\n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = georgegadsonstudios.com\n| born             = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| residence        = \n}}\n\n== 1\tEarly life and education ==\nGeorge Gadson (born August 10,[1] 1953) is an American artist living and working in Florida.\n\nFlorida native artist George Gadson was born and raised in Fort Meade, Florida.[2] From cleaning his family\u2019s outhouse[3] in the small Central Florida town of Fort Meade, to George and Laura Bush\u2019s White House[4] as the artist commissioned to design the Christmas Ornament for the tree in 2008[5], this artist, sculptor and community advocate maintains pride about his home town roots and humility for his journey into art and sports signature awards. \n\nGadson graduated Fort Meade High School.And began his studies at the Duke University, North Carolina in 1991 at the age of 30. He earned a BFA in Theology in 1995 and an MFA in 1997.\n\n== 2\tWork ==\nGeorge Gadson has gained state-wide[9] recognition for his realistic portraits and sculptures of individuals and figures that have historical significance. His work is displayed throughout South Florida in many venues for Public Art, as well as in the homes of and collections of several national notable personalities.\n=== 2.1\tOther projects ===\nWorking in a variety of mediums Gadson has created bronze relief portrait sculptures of Jim Moran, Moran Foundation and Founder Bill Darden for Darden Restaurants, Inc. owners of Olive Garden and Red Lobster. His public works are permanently displayed in the International Swimming Hall of Fame, the African American Research Library and Cultural Center, the City of Lauderhill, the City of Tamarac, the City of Pompano Beach, to name a few of the significant locations around the county.\n\nHis work can also be seen throughout South Florida in Miami-Dade and Palm Beach Counties, and nationally in the private collection of Harry Belafonte; and one of his significant sculptures is part of Venus Williams\u2019 artwork collection, given as an award to Williams by the City of Lauderhill. Gadson has also been publicly recognized for his work with children, young adults and under-served communities, through distress programs; speaking about art and creativity within the education system; art as a communication and healing medium for team-building resolution; and murals for cause through his not-for-profit organization, 'Art Turnatives for Building Communities.' In 2017, Gadson was invited to design and present a sculpture to Baltimore Raven\u2019s retired Linebacker and Pro Football Hall of Famer Ray Lewis. No stranger to football royalty, Gadson has been designing for highly-profiled persons in sports and politics since as far back as the 90s. This was a repeat honor and invitation for Gadson from the South Florida Superbowl Host Committee, as in 1995 and 1999 he created two South Florida Super Bowl bronze commemorative sculptures aptly named, \u201cThe Quarterback\u201d and the \u201cThe Kicker,\u201d for each of the NFL Team owners as well as other significant VIPs.\n\n== 3\tArt + Practice ==\n== 4\tExhibitions ==\n== 5\tHonors and awards ==\n== 6\tArt market ==\n== 7\tMedia ==\n== 8\tSelected bibliography ==\n== 9\tSee also ==\n== 10\tReferences ==\n== 11\tExternal links ==\n", "text_old": "{{Prod blp/dated\n  |concern = \n  |user = \n  |timestamp = 20200416055337\n  |help = off\n}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = GeorgeGadson\n| image            = Geroge the Classic.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = GeorgeGadson in 2020\n| birth_name       = <!--only use if different from name-->\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1961|11|20}}\n| birth_place      = [[Los Angeles]]\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = American\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = <nowiki>[[Duke University]</nowiki>\n| known_for        = abstract painting, performance art\n| notable_works    = Pickett's Charge (2017), Bell Tower (LAX) (2017), Yellow Bird (2012), Helter Skelter I (2007), Los Moscos (2004)\n| style            = \n| movement         = [[Contemporary Art]]\n| awards           = MacArthur Genius Award, US Department of State Medal of Arts, Bucksbaum Award\n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| born             = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| residence        = \n}}\n\n== 1\tEarly life and education ==\nGeorge Gadson (born August 10,[1] 1953) is an American artist living and working in Florida.\n\nFlorida native artist George Gadson was born and raised in Fort Meade, Florida.[2] From cleaning his family\u2019s outhouse[3] in the small Central Florida town of Fort Meade, to George and Laura Bush\u2019s White House[4] as the artist commissioned to design the Christmas Ornament for the tree in 2008[5], this artist, sculptor and community advocate maintains pride about his home town roots and humility for his journey into art and sports signature awards. \n\nGadson graduated Fort Meade High School.And began his studies at the Duke University, North Carolina in 1991 at the age of 30. He earned a BFA in Theology in 1995 and an MFA in 1997.\n\n== 2\tWork ==\nGeorge Gadson has gained state-wide[9] recognition for his realistic portraits and sculptures of individuals and figures that have historical significance. His work is displayed throughout South Florida in many venues for Public Art, as well as in the homes of and collections of several national notable personalities.\n=== 2.1\tOther projects ===\nWorking in a variety of mediums Gadson has created bronze relief portrait sculptures of Jim Moran, Moran Foundation and Founder Bill Darden for Darden Restaurants, Inc. owners of Olive Garden and Red Lobster. His public works are permanently displayed in the International Swimming Hall of Fame, the African American Research Library and Cultural Center, the City of Lauderhill, the City of Tamarac, the City of Pompano Beach, to name a few of the significant locations around the county.\n\nHis work can also be seen throughout South Florida in Miami-Dade and Palm Beach Counties, and nationally in the private collection of Harry Belafonte; and one of his significant sculptures is part of Venus Williams\u2019 artwork collection, given as an award to Williams by the City of Lauderhill. Gadson has also been publicly recognized for his work with children, young adults and under-served communities, through distress programs; speaking about art and creativity within the education system; art as a communication and healing medium for team-building resolution; and murals for cause through his not-for-profit organization, 'Art Turnatives for Building Communities.' In 2017, Gadson was invited to design and present a sculpture to Baltimore Raven\u2019s retired Linebacker and Pro Football Hall of Famer Ray Lewis. No stranger to football royalty, Gadson has been designing for highly-profiled persons in sports and politics since as far back as the 90s. This was a repeat honor and invitation for Gadson from the South Florida Superbowl Host Committee, as in 1995 and 1999 he created two South Florida Super Bowl bronze commemorative sculptures aptly named, \u201cThe Quarterback\u201d and the \u201cThe Kicker,\u201d for each of the NFL Team owners as well as other significant VIPs.\n\n== 3\tArt + Practice ==\n== 4\tExhibitions ==\n== 5\tHonors and awards ==\n== 6\tArt market ==\n== 7\tMedia ==\n== 8\tSelected bibliography ==\n== 9\tSee also ==\n== 10\tReferences ==\n== 11\tExternal links ==\n", "name_user": "SwanComm13", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Gadson"}
{"title_page": "Coombs Dale", "text_new": "{{short description|Valley in the Derbyshire Peak District}}\n\n{{Infobox valley|name=Coombs Dale|coordinates_ref=<!-- Statistics -->|photo=Above Coombs Dale - geograph.org.uk - 1365773.jpg|photo_size=|photo_alt=|photo_caption=View across Coombs Dale|map_image=|map_size=|elevation=|map_caption=|location=[[Derbyshire]], [[England]]|relief=|label=|label_position=|coordinates={{Coord|53.2681|-1.6750|display=title, inline|type:valley}}|map_alt=|elevation_ft=|other_name=|elevation_m=|footnotes=|watercourses=|traversed=|towns=|topo=|boundaries=|type=|depth={{Convert|150|m|0}}|width={{Convert|450|m|0}}|length={{Convert|1.9|mi|0}}|direction=West-East|elevation_ref=|embed=}}{{Use dmy dates|date = April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Limestone outcrop above Coombs Dale - geograph.org.uk - 602950.jpg|thumb|Limestone outcrop above Coombs Dale]]\n'''Coombs Dale''' is a steep-sided, dry [[Carboniferous Limestone|carboniferous limestone]] valley in the [[Derbyshire]] [[Peak District]] of England. The village of [[Calver]] lies abot 1&nbsp;km to the east and the village of [[Stoney Middleton]] lies less than 1&nbsp;km to the north. The dale is cut into the hills on the east side of Longstone Moor. The upper end of the dale is known as Rough Side. Several springs flow down the dale during winter and after heavy rains.<ref name=\"OS\">[[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Explorer'' map OL24E, 1:25,000 series.</ref>\n\nThe fossil-rich limestone was formed from deposits in a warm shallow sea in the [[Vis\u00e9an|Brigantian]] stage of the [[Carboniferous]] period (around 330 million years ago). Coombs Dale is a designated [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] (SSSI). Ash trees and hazel grow on the scree slopes of the dale sides. Varied shrubs and wild flowers includes [[Cornus sanguinea|dogwood]], [[Prunus spinosa|blackthorn]], [[Helianthemum nummularium|common rock-rose]], [[Thymus praecox|wild thyme]], [[Geranium sanguineum|bloody cranesbill]], [[Lily of the valley|lily-of-the-valley]], [[Melica nutans|mountain melick]], rare [[Epipactis atrorubens|dark-red helleborine]] and orchids. The local limestone fern ''Gymnocarpium robertianum'' thrives on the scree and the rare fingered sedge ''Carex digitata'' can be found in places. Grazed natives grasses are mainly [[Helictotrichon pratense|meadow oat-grass]] and [[Carex flacca|glaucous sedge]]. The dale is also habitat for [[dark green fritillary]] and [[Aricia agestis|brown argus]] butterflies.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/PDFsForWeb/Citation/1002717.pdf|title=Coombs Dale SSSI|last=|first=|date=|website=Designated Site \u2013 Natural England|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 18th-century, a notorious highwayman called Black Harry ambushed and robbed travellers crossing the local moors. Black Harry Gate is at the head of the dale, leading onto Black Harry Lane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0022/48073/blackharry.pdf|title=The Black Harry Trails|last=|first=|date=|website=Peak District National Park|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nLongstone Edge, above the south side of the dale, has been mined for minerals for many centuries. Lead mining heaps and beehive mine shafts are spread across the terrain. Nearby Cavendish Mill has been a processing centre for [[Fluorite|fluorspar]] since 1965. Sallet Hole Mine is a 19th-century fluorspar mine in the centre of Coombs Dale, which closed in 1998. There is a disused quarry at the foot of Coombs Dale.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://smhccg.org/wp-content/uploads/Bulletin-11-3-Fluorspar-Mining-in-Derbyshire.pdf|title=Fluorspar Mining in Derbyshire|last=Bramley|first=J.V.|date=1991|website=Stoney Middleton Heritage Centre|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdmhs.co.uk/stoney-middleton-circular-walk/|title=Stoney Middleton Mining Heritage Walk Report|last=|first=|date=|website=PEAK DISTRICT MINES HISTORICAL SOCIETY|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nCombs Dale is designated as \"Open Access\" land for the public, following the [[Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.openaccess.naturalengland.org.uk/wps/portal/oasys/maps/MapSearch/|title=CRoW and Coastal Access Maps|last=|first=|date=|website=Natural England|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> There is an easy-going footpath along the length of the valley floor. There is access into the dale from both ends, as well as footpaths from Stoney Middleton and Calver into into the central section of the valley.<ref name=\"OS\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Valleys of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Peak District]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Valley in the Derbyshire Peak District}}\n\n{{Infobox valley|name=Coombs Dale|coordinates_ref=<!-- Statistics -->|photo=Above Coombs Dale - geograph.org.uk - 1365773.jpg|photo_size=|photo_alt=|photo_caption=View across Coombs Dale|map_image=|map_size=|elevation=|map_caption=|location=[[Derbyshire]], [[England]]|relief=|label=|label_position=|coordinates={{Coord|53.2681|-1.6750|display=title, inline|type:valley}}|map_alt=|elevation_ft=|other_name=|elevation_m=|footnotes=|watercourses=|traversed=|towns=|topo=|boundaries=|type=|depth={{Convert|150|m|0}}|width={{Convert|450|m|0}}|length={{Convert|1.9|mi|0}}|direction=West-East|elevation_ref=|embed=}}{{Use dmy dates|date = April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Limestone outcrop above Coombs Dale - geograph.org.uk - 602950.jpg|thumb|Limestone outcrop above Coombs Dale]]\n'''Coombs Dale''' is a steep-sided, dry [[Carboniferous Limestone|carboniferous limestone]] valley in the [[Derbyshire]] [[Peak District]] of England. The village of [[Calver]] lies abot 1km to the east and the village of [[Stoney Middleton]] lies less than 1km to the north. The dale is cut into the hills on the east side of Longstone Moor. The upper end of the dale is known as Rough Side. Several springs flow down the dale during winter and after heavy rains.<ref name=\"OS\">[[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Explorer'' map OL24E, 1:25,000 series.</ref>\n\nThe fossil-rich limestone was formed from deposits in a warm shallow sea in the [[Vis\u00e9an|Brigantian]] stage of the [[Carboniferous]] period (around 330 million years ago). Coombs Dale is a designated [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] (SSSI). Ash trees and hazel grow on the scree slopes of the dale sides. Varied shrubs and wild flowers includes [[Cornus sanguinea|dogwood]], [[Prunus spinosa|blackthorn]], [[Helianthemum nummularium|common rock-rose]], [[Thymus praecox|wild thyme]], [[Geranium sanguineum|bloody cranesbill]], [[Lily of the valley|lily-of-the-valley]], [[Melica nutans|mountain melick]], rare [[Epipactis atrorubens|dark-red helleborine]] and orchids. The local limestone fern ''Gymnocarpium robertianum'' thrives on the scree and the rare fingered sedge ''Carex digitata'' can be found in places. Grazed natives grasses are mainly [[Helictotrichon pratense|meadow oat-grass]] and [[Carex flacca|glaucous sedge]]. The dale is also habitat for [[dark green fritillary]] and [[Aricia agestis|brown argus]] butterflies.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/PDFsForWeb/Citation/1002717.pdf|title=Coombs Dale SSSI|last=|first=|date=|website=Designated Site \u2013 Natural England|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 18th-century, a notorious highwayman called Black Harry ambushed and robbed travellers crossing the local moors. Black Harry Gate is at the head of the dale, leading onto Black Harry Lane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0022/48073/blackharry.pdf|title=The Black Harry Trails|last=|first=|date=|website=Peak District National Park|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nLongstone Edge, above the south side of the dale, has been mined for minerals for many centuries. Lead mining heaps and beehive mine shafts are spread across the terrain. Nearby Cavendish Mill has been a processing centre for [[Fluorite|fluorspar]] since 1965. Sallet Hole Mine is a 19th-century fluorspar mine in the centre of Coombs Dale, which closed in 1998. There is a disused quarry at the foot of Coombs Dale.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://smhccg.org/wp-content/uploads/Bulletin-11-3-Fluorspar-Mining-in-Derbyshire.pdf|title=Fluorspar Mining in Derbyshire|last=Bramley|first=J.V.|date=1991|website=Stoney Middleton Heritage Centre|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdmhs.co.uk/stoney-middleton-circular-walk/|title=Stoney Middleton Mining Heritage Walk Report|last=|first=|date=|website=PEAK DISTRICT MINES HISTORICAL SOCIETY|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nCombs Dale is designated as \"Open Access\" land for the public, following the [[Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.openaccess.naturalengland.org.uk/wps/portal/oasys/maps/MapSearch/|title=CRoW and Coastal Access Maps|last=|first=|date=|website=Natural England|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> There is a easy-going footpath along the length of the valley floor. There is access into the dale from both ends, as well as footpaths from Stoney Middleton and Calver into into the central section of the valley.<ref name=\"OS\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:Valleys of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Peak District]]\n", "na